Cell["\<\
1. Using your dashboard, find the minimum input current needed to make the \
neuron fire at least one
spike (with default threshold and tau). This is called the rheobase. What \
value did you find?

I found that the neuron starts firing at about\[NonBreakingSpace]16 nA, so \
the rheobase is just above\[NonBreakingSpace]15 nA\[NonBreakingSpace]with the \
default threshold and tau.

2. Set the current to 25 nA. Now slowly increase the threshold from -65 to \
-45 mV. At what threshold
does the neuron stop firing? Why?

As I increased the threshold from\[NonBreakingSpace]-65 to -45 mV, the neuron \
stopped firing at about\[NonBreakingSpace]-45 mV. This happens because the \
membrane potential can only approach its steady value (around\
\[NonBreakingSpace]-45 mV) and cannot reach a threshold higher than that.

3. Set threshold to -55 and current to 20. Compare tau = 0.010 vs tau = \
0.050. Which produces more
spikes? Which produces a smoother membrane potential curve?

When I compared\[NonBreakingSpace]\[Tau] = 0.010\[NonBreakingSpace]and\
\[NonBreakingSpace]\[Tau] = 0.050, I saw that\[NonBreakingSpace]\[Tau] = \
0.010 produced more spikes\[NonBreakingSpace]because the voltage rises \
faster.\[NonBreakingSpace]\[Tau] = 0.050 produced a smoother membrane \
potential curve\[NonBreakingSpace]because the voltage changes more slowly.

The Manipulate[] dashboard lets you explore neuron behavior interactively in \
a way that static code cannot. Describe one insight you gained from adjusting \
the sliders that you did NOT get from reading the booklet. How did the visual \
feedback change your understanding?

By adjusting the sliders, I realized how sensitive the neuron\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s firing is to the\[NonBreakingSpace]input current and \
threshold. When I increased the current, the neuron started firing more \
frequently, and when I raised the threshold, it sometimes stopped firing \
completely. 
Seeing this happen in real time helped me understand that the neuron only \
spikes when the membrane potential can actually reach the threshold. The \
visual feedback made it clearer how the parameters directly control whether \
and how often spikes occur.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"48360b65-65e4-466b-906e-cafcf1eb5d3d"],

