Cell["\<\
Answer (what happens & why):

The spike pattern is\[NonBreakingSpace]not the same each time.

Because the input current includes\[NonBreakingSpace]random fluctuations, the \
exact times when\[NonBreakingSpace]V(t)\[NonBreakingSpace]reaches threshold \
shift from run to run, so spikes can appear/disappear or move in time.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c7e94626-1d2d-479b-82da-2c05b835cfb0"],

Cell["\<\

Experiment 1: Threshold Sweep

I changed the\[NonBreakingSpace]threshold\[NonBreakingSpace]from\
\[NonBreakingSpace]-65 to -45 mV\[NonBreakingSpace]in steps of\
\[NonBreakingSpace]5 mV.

I expected that increasing the threshold would make \
it\[NonBreakingSpace]harder for the neuron to spike, so the spike count would \
decrease.

I observed that as the threshold increased, the\[NonBreakingSpace]number of \
spikes decreased, and eventually the neuron stopped firing.

This makes sense because in the\[NonBreakingSpace]LIF equation, the membrane \
potential must reach the threshold to trigger a spike. A higher threshold \
means the voltage has to rise further, which happens less often.

Experiment 2: Time Constant Comparison

I changed the\[NonBreakingSpace]time constant \[Tau]\[NonBreakingSpace]to\
\[NonBreakingSpace]0.010, 0.020, and 0.050 seconds.

I expected that a\[NonBreakingSpace]smaller \[Tau] would make the membrane \
potential change faster, while a larger \[Tau] would make it change more \
slowly.

I observed that\[NonBreakingSpace]\[Tau] = 0.010 produced faster voltage \
changes and more spikes, while\[NonBreakingSpace]\[Tau] = 0.050 produced \
slower and smoother voltage curves with fewer spikes.

This makes sense because \[Tau] controls how quickly the membrane potential \
responds to input in the LIF equation.

Experiment 3: Noisy Input

I changed the\[NonBreakingSpace]input current\[NonBreakingSpace]from a \
constant value to a\[NonBreakingSpace]noisy current:\[NonBreakingSpace]18 + \
RandomReal[\[Minus]8,8].

I expected the spike pattern to become\[NonBreakingSpace]less regular\
\[NonBreakingSpace]because the input current would fluctuate randomly.

I observed that the\[NonBreakingSpace]spike timing changed each time I ran \
the simulation, so the spike pattern was different in every run.

This makes sense because random fluctuations in the input current change when \
the membrane potential reaches the threshold, which leads to different spike \
times.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f60720c4-f830-41ee-98e2-ceff4de3ee8d"],

Cell["\<\

Reflections

1. Increasing input current:
As I gradually increased the input current from below threshold to above it, \
the neuron did not fire at first. Once the current passed a certain level \
(around 16 nA), the neuron started firing spikes. As I increased the current \
further, the spikes happened more frequently. 
This shows that neurons have a threshold behavior, meaning they only fire \
when the input is strong enough, which is similar to how biological neurons \
make decisions about whether to send a signal.

2. f\[Dash]I curve:
When I looked at the f\[Dash]I curve, the relationship between input current \
and spike count was not perfectly linear. The firing rate increased as \
current increased, but the increase was not exactly constant. 
This suggests that neurons encode stimulus intensity through changes in \
firing rate, but the relationship can be nonlinear.

3. Membrane time constant:
When I changed the membrane time constant, I saw that smaller \[Tau] values \
caused the neuron to respond faster and produce more spikes, while larger \
\[Tau] values produced slower changes in voltage and fewer spikes. \
Biologically, neurons with short time constants might respond quickly to \
rapid inputs, while neurons with long time constants might integrate signals \
over longer periods.

4. Comparing the LIF model to real neurons:
The LIF model captures the basic idea of membrane potential integration, \
threshold firing, and spike resets. However, it misses many important \
features of real neurons, such as complex dendrite structures, multiple ion \
channels, neurotransmitter effects, and spike adaptation. Real neurons are \
much more complex than the simplified LIF model.

5. Using Manipulate:
Using Manipulate[] helped me understand neuron behavior much better because I \
could see the effects of changing parameters immediately. Instead of just \
reading about how parameters affect firing, I could visually observe it in \
real time. 
The most surprising thing I noticed was how small parameter changes, like \
threshold or current, could dramatically change whether the neuron fired or \
stayed silent.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"50a9d1da-7215-4fe7-8e33-76180a1f946a"]
},
